Some updates since the last time:

After the C tokenizer refactoring the segfault happens in the `call_def_func` function, now at `mwparserfromhell/parser/ctokenizer/tok_parse.c:96`. After reading [this introduction](https://docs.python.org/3/c-api/intro.html), I've come to the conclusion that there is missing exception handling. In fact, I don't see any exception handling anywhere in the C tokenizer.

If we modify `call_def_func` to look at the error indicator:
```C
static int call_def_func(const char* funcname, PyObject* in1, PyObject* in2)
{
    PyObject* func = PyObject_GetAttrString(definitions, funcname);
    PyObject* result = PyObject_CallFunctionObjArgs(func, in1, in2, NULL);
    int ans = (result == Py_True) ? 1 : 0;

    if( result == NULL )
        PyErr_PrintEx(0);

    Py_DECREF(func);
    Py_DECREF(result);
    return ans;
}
```
the output will be the following:
```
^CTraceback (most recent call last):
  File "/usr/lib/python3.4/site-packages/mwparserfromhell/definitions.py", line 84, in is_scheme
    def is_scheme(scheme, slashes=True):
KeyboardInterrupt
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
```
so the segfault comes from decrefing a `NULL` value.

If this is the only place in the C tokenizer where arbitrary Python code gets executed, it is only logical that the `KeyboardInterrupt` happens here, because here the tokenizer most likely spends most time, but principally it might happen anywhere. Incidentally it may be interesting to port `definitions.py` to C for better performance.

I've used this minimal example for testing, along with the content of [this page](https://wiki.archlinux.org/index.php/AMD_Catalyst). Hopefully you'll be able to reproduce this, because I don't see any platform-specific issue.
```python
import sys
import mwparserfromhell

if len(sys.argv) != 2:
    print("usage: {} path_to_file".format(sys.argv[0]))
    sys.exit(1)

f = open(sys.argv[1], "r")
text = f.read()

for i in range(10):
    print(i)
    mwparserfromhell.parse(text)
```

