I only took a quick (not thorough) look at #3841. Replacing the `print` calls is good, but otherwise I'm not really sold on that approach. I think the only benefit of the `Message` class is to have a dedicated `message_name` attribute, but that's it, more or less. The same thing (and more) can be accomplished by just using a `logging.Formatter`. This gives much more flexibility since then not only the message text but the whole `LogRecord` (incl. log levels and the like, or exceptions obtained with the `exc_info` argument) can be (JSON) formatted.
Maybe something similar to this:
```python
class ContextFormatter(Formatter):
    def format(self, record):
        if context.json:
            msg_dict = {}
            args = record.args
            if isinstance(args, collections.abc.Mapping) and "message_name" in args:
                msg_dict["message_name"] = record.args["message_name"]
            msg_dict["args"] = record.args
            return json.dumps(msg_dict)
        if context.quiet
            [...]
        return super(ContextFormatter, self).format(record)

stdoutlog = getLogger("conda.stdout")
handler = StdStreamHandler("stdout")
handler.setFormatter(ContextFormatter("%(message)s"))
stdoutlog.addHandler(handler)

stdoutlog.info("user message: %(some_kwarg)", dict(message_name="user_message", some_kwargs="hey there")
```

