I have actually considered use cases like this before and it is something I would like satpy to be able to do (read data from other sources besides directly on disk). One thing that should work for you, but it is not heavily tested, is to provider a `Reader` instance as the `reader` argument to the `Scene` rather than add a new keyword argument to the Scene.

This also isn't a simple thing that we would want users to have to "manually" do in their own code so we would want to add this internally in to satpy's readers, perhaps even to a specific set of readers. Put another way, expecting users to make custom file reading utilities (using bz2, etc) that get passed to the existing reader interfaces doesn't make sense as an interface. The reader classes and the file handler classes they user are there for a reason. We also depend heavily on dask and xarray which may already have solutions for lazy-loading compressed data.

@sfinkens Do you expect to need other file formats (more than just HSD) to be readable from compressed files too? This seems like it is very specific to what the format is and if the libraries used underneath can handle compressed data well. I think the right way to implement this type of functionality is to customize/subclass or add on to the existing reader or file handlers. In your current example you are actually reading the data files in to memory. It may be best/preferred to include this type of logic in a dask Delayed function so that the data isn't loaded in to memory until it is actually needed (like all other dask functionality).

